 Workflow Authoring Guide

## File Convention

Create or update a workflow with the `create_or_update_workflow` tool (args: `name`, `description`, `trigger`, `definition`). That is the ONLY way to register/activate one.
- Writing a `.jsonc` with `write_file` does NOT register a workflow (no definition, schedule, or triggers) — never use it to create or edit workflows.
- `read_file("base44/workflows/")` lists existing workflow files (read-only mirror in code view).
- Each save is a new version; running workflows keep their started version. After a successful save the workflow is immediately active.

## Managing Workflow Status

Use the `manage_workflow` tool — NOT file edits — to change a workflow's lifecycle status:
- `activate` — resume a paused workflow (its triggers/schedules go live again)
- `deactivate` — pause a workflow (stops triggering; keeps the definition and file intact)
- `archive` — soft-delete (removes schedules and the file). This is how you delete a workflow.
- `unarchive` — restore an archived workflow. It comes back **live** unless its schedule already ended, in which case it's restored **paused** (the result tells you which).

Look up the target workflow by name from the workflows list below (archived ones are listed separately).

## Envelope Format

```json
{
  "name": "Human-Readable Workflow Name",
  "description": "What this workflow does",
  "trigger": { ... },
  "definition": { ... }
}
```

## CNCF Serverless Workflow v1.0 Definition

```json
{
  "document": { "dsl": "1.0.0", "name": "snake_case_id", "version": "1.0", "namespace": "base44" },
  "do": [
    { "task_name": { "call": "activity_name", "with": {}, "then": "next_task" } }
  ]
}
```

**Task naming**: must be snake_case (letters, digits, underscores). Task results are accessed in jq as `${ .task_name.field }` — hyphens break jq field access. Never start a task name with `__` (double underscore) — that namespace is reserved for system steps and the save will be rejected.

**MANDATORY transitions** — there is no implicit sequential fallback; violations cause validation errors:
- Every `call` and `wait` task must have a `then` field: the name of the next task or `"end"` to terminate.
- `switch` tasks branch ONLY through their cases: every case must have its own `then`, the **last case must be the catch-all `{"when": "${ true }", "then": ...}`** ("otherwise"), and the switch task itself must NOT have a task-level `then`.
- A switch needs at least one real condition case besides the catch-all. A switch whose only case is `${ true }` is a no-op and is rejected.

**Execution model: strictly sequential.** Tasks run one at a time in `then` order — there is NO parallel execution, fork/join, or "branches running at the same time". Never fabricate "fan-out" / "converge" marker nodes (e.g. a pass-through switch) to make the graph look parallel: the graph would misrepresent what actually runs. If the user asks for parallel branches, explain that steps execute in sequence and model the flow as ordered steps.

## Supported Task Types

### call — invoke a registered activity
```json
{ "fetch_data": { "call": "invoke_backend_function", "with": { "function_name": "getData", "args": {} }, "then": "next_task" } }
```

### switch — conditional branching
```json
{ "check": { "switch": [
    { "when": "${ .fetch_data.status == \"active\" }", "then": "handle_active" },
    { "when": "${ true }", "then": "end" }
] } }
```
Cases are evaluated in order — the first truthy `when` wins. Every case MUST have its own `then`. The last case MUST be the catch-all `${ true }` ("otherwise") so every run takes an explicit, visible branch. Do NOT put a `then` on the switch task itself — with an exhaustive case list it would be dead code, and validation rejects it.

### wait — durable time delay (survives restarts)
```json
{ "pause": { "wait": "PT5M", "then": "next_task" } }
```
ISO 8601: PT5M = 5 min, PT1H = 1 hour, P1D = 1 day, P3DT12H = 3.5 days

## `x-base44` (display-only node labels - set on every task)

Use `x-base44` on every task you author for graph labels only. It does not change runtime behavior, task output, transitions, trigger matching, or activity inputs. Allowed sub-fields (anything else is rejected):

- `title`: string - node title. **Always set this in the user's language, matching the language they use with you.** The task key stays `snake_case` ASCII for engine/jq access and is not a good UI label.
- `description`: string - short node subtitle. Optional; use it when it clarifies what the task currently does. Keep it **very short** (a few words).

```json
{ "fetch_data": {
    "call": "invoke_backend_function",
    "with": { "function_name": "getData" },
    "then": "next_task",
    "x-base44": { "title": "Fetch order", "description": "Latest record" }
} }
```

When editing an existing workflow, preserve `x-base44` for tasks whose purpose did not change. If a task's user-visible meaning changes, update its `title`/`description` to match. Do not carry stale labels.

## Available Activities

### compute_seconds_until
Compute seconds from now until a target datetime.
- `target_iso`: ISO 8601 datetime string
- Returns: {"seconds": float, "target_iso": str, "now_iso": str}

### invoke_backend_function
Call a deployed Deno backend function.
- When to use: Logic you write as code: API calls, data fetching/transforms, entity CRUD, sending email/HTTP. You control exactly what it does — no agent reasoning turn.
- `function_name`: Name of the backend function to call
- `args`: Dict of arguments passed as the function request body (supports jq expressions)
- Returns: Parsed JSON response from the function

### invoke_superagent_step
Send a message to the superagent LLM and get a response.
- When to use: Hands the step to the agent — it decides what to do, can use the agent's tools, connectors, memory, and channels, and costs credits each run. Reach for it only when a step genuinely needs that: judgment, natural-language composition, or user-facing delivery. Anything you can express as explicit code or a specific action belongs in a backend function (or another activity). Typical shape: other steps gather and act, then an LLM step composes and broadcasts; if nothing needs the agent, skip it.
- `message`: Prompt to send to the AI agent. Shown to the user in the task view — write it readable: use line breaks between steps or sections instead of one dense paragraph.
- Returns: {"agent_response": str, "credits_charged": float}

## Choosing Between Activities

See each activity's "When to use" line above for what it's best at.

## jq Expression Language

Use `${ .field }` syntax (CNCF SWF v1.0).
- Trigger data: `${ .trigger.data.fieldname }`
- Task output: `${ .task_name.field }`
- Conditions: `${ .trigger.data.status == "active" }`
- String interpolation: `"Hello ${ .trigger.data.name }"`

**Write jq, not JavaScript/Python.** Common mistakes to avoid:
- Logic operators are `and` / `or` / `not`, never `&&` / `||` / `!`: `${ .trigger.data.a == 1 and .trigger.data.b != 2 }`.
- Membership is `${ .trigger.data.event.channel | IN("C1","C2") }`, never infix `x in [...]`.
- String tests (`test` / `contains` / `startswith` / `ascii_downcase`) throw on a null field — default first: `${ (.trigger.data.subject // "") | test("receipt"; "i") }`.
- Iteration throws on null — default with `// []`: `${ any((.trigger.data.items // [])[]; .qty > 0) }`.
- In a pipe, `.` is the piped value, not the root — bind root refs first: `${ .trigger.data.event.channel as $c | ["C1","C2"] | index($c) != null }`.

## Trigger Types

The trigger object wraps the type-specific fields (shown below) in `config`, plus an optional `condition`:
```json
{ "config": { "trigger_type": "entity", "entity_name": "orders", "events": ["update"] }, "condition": "${ .trigger.data.status == \"pending\" }" }
```

### scheduled
```json
{ "trigger_type": "scheduled", "cron_expression": "0 9 * * 1-5", "timezone": "America/New_York" }
```

**Timezone**: The user's timezone is available in the `<user_timezone_info>` tag in developer_comments. When the user mentions times (e.g., "9am", "2pm", "midnight"), they mean times in THEIR timezone. Set the `timezone` field to the user's timezone — the cron expression is then evaluated in that timezone (no manual UTC conversion needed).

Cron format: `minute hour day-of-month month day-of-week`

**Choose cron vs interval FIRST.** Cron fires at clock-aligned times, so a "every N <unit>" request is only expressible in cron when N evenly divides its field's wrap period — minutes where N divides 60 (1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 10, 12, 15, 20, 30) or hours where N divides 24 (1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 8, 12). For any other fixed gap — "every 90 minutes", "every 45 minutes", "every 7 hours", "every 2 days" — cron CANNOT express it: use **interval mode** (see below). Never approximate with `*/90 * * * *` (most cron parsers reduce the out-of-range minute step to :00, collapsing it to hourly — some reject it outright) or `0 9 */2 * *` (the day-of-month step restarts every month, so it is not a true 2-day gap).

Translating user requests to cron (clock-aligned cadences):
- "every 5 minutes" → `*/5 * * * *` (minimum interval)
- "every hour" / "hourly" → `0 * * * *`
- "every day at 9am" / "daily at 9" → `0 9 * * *`
- "every weekday at 9am" / "Monday to Friday" → `0 9 * * 1-5`
- "every Monday at 10am" → `0 10 * * 1`
- "every Monday and Friday at 10am" → `0 10 * * 1,5`
- "every month on the 15th" → `0 0 15 * *`
- "every month on the 1st at 9am" → `0 9 1 * *`
- "twice a day at 9am and 5pm" → `0 9,17 * * *`
- "every 30 minutes during business hours" → `*/30 9-17 * * 1-5`
- "every Sunday at midnight" → `0 0 * * 0`

**Run once** (instead of recurring): set `schedule_mode` to `"one_time"` with a future UTC instant — no cron_expression needed:
```json
{ "trigger_type": "scheduled", "schedule_mode": "one_time", "one_time_date": "2026-07-01T16:00:00Z" }
```
`one_time_date` is a future UTC instant. Never guess "now" — take the current local time from the `<user_timezone_info>` tag, resolve the user's request against it (relative "in N minutes" or a clock time like "9:12am"), then convert to UTC.

**Recurring at a fixed interval** — use this for any "every N minutes/hours/days" the cron rule above says cron can't express (e.g. "every 90 minutes", "every 45 minutes", "every 7 hours", "every 2 days"). Set `schedule_mode` to `"interval"` and DO NOT set `cron_expression`:
```json
{ "trigger_type": "scheduled", "schedule_mode": "interval", "interval_value": 2, "interval_unit": "days", "interval_anchor": "2026-07-01T09:00:00Z" }
```
Units: minutes | hours | days only. Minimum interval is 5 minutes. `interval_anchor` (UTC) sets the phase — when the user gives a time-of-day or start ("every 2 days at 9am", "every 90 minutes starting 14:00") set it to that UTC instant; omit it to align to the epoch. For calendar cadences (specific weekdays, day-of-month, weekly, monthly) use cron.

**End conditions** (recurring schedules only, default is run forever):
- Stop on a date: add `"ends_type": "on_date", "ends_on_date": "2026-12-31T23:59:00Z"` — the last instant the schedule may fire (UTC).
- Stop after N runs: add `"ends_type": "after_count", "ends_after_count": 10`.

When a schedule finishes (one-time fired, end date passed, or run count reached) the workflow is automatically archived.

### entity
```json
{ "trigger_type": "entity", "entity_name": "orders", "events": ["create", "update"] }
```

Trigger payload structure:
- `${ .trigger.entity_name }` — entity name (e.g. "orders")
- `${ .trigger.entity_id }` — the entity record ID
- `${ .trigger.event_type }` — "create", "update", or "delete"
- `${ .trigger.data.* }` — current entity data
- `${ .trigger.old_data.* }` — previous data (update events only)
- `${ .trigger.changed_fields }` — array of top-level field names that changed
- `${ .trigger.payload_too_large }` — true when the record was too large to attach (see note below)

Condition examples:
- Only when status changes to "completed":
  `"condition": "${ .trigger.data.status == \"completed\" and .trigger.old_data.status != \"completed\" }"`
- Only when a specific field changed:
  `"condition": "${ .trigger.changed_fields | index(\"status\") != null }"`
- Only for a specific entity value:
  `"condition": "${ .trigger.data.priority == \"high\" }"`

Note: when the entity record is very large (over ~256KB), `data` and `old_data` arrive as null and `payload_too_large` is true (`changed_fields` stays populated). Trigger conditions still evaluate against the full data, but the backend function must re-fetch the record by id using the Base44 SDK: `await base44.entities.get("entity_name", entity_id)`.

Use `read_file("base44/entities/<EntityName>.jsonc")` to check entity field names before writing conditions.

### connector
```json
{"trigger_type": "connector", "integration_type": "slack", "events": ["message"]}
```

Optional: `resource_id` — for Google Calendar (calendar ID, e.g. "primary" or "user@gmail.com") or Google Drive (file ID). Controls which webhook registration is used (scopes the provider subscription, not per-workflow dispatch filtering).
```json
{"trigger_type": "connector", "integration_type": "googlecalendar", "events": ["events"], "resource_id": "primary"}
```

Prerequisites:
- The connector must be authorized (use `get_connectors_info` and `request_oauth_authorization`). The webhook registration is set up automatically when the workflow is saved.
- Each provider has a different payload structure and auth model. Always call `get_connectors_info` with the integration type to get the provider-specific webhook handler guide BEFORE writing the backend function.

Trigger payload:
- `${ .trigger.integration_type }` — e.g. "slack", "googlecalendar"
- `${ .trigger.event_type }` — the webhook event type
- `${ .trigger.data.* }` — the raw webhook payload from the provider
- `${ .trigger.payload_too_large }` — true when the webhook payload was too large to attach (over ~256KB); `data` arrives as null (conditions still evaluate against the full payload) and the backend function must re-fetch the resource from the provider

Condition field paths use the provider's webhook payload structure:
- Slack: `${ .trigger.data.event.channel == \"C0123ABC\" }`, `${ .trigger.data.event.user == \"U0123ABC\" }`
- Google Calendar: `${ .trigger.data.resource_id == \"calendar_id\" }`

**Important**: When the user provides a human-readable name (e.g. "#general"), the webhook payload uses internal IDs. Resolve the name to an ID first: create a temporary backend function that uses the authorized connector to look up the ID, run it with `test_backend_function`, then use the returned ID in the condition. Never guess IDs.

High-volume connectors (e.g. Slack) require conditions — validation will reject triggers without them.

Available connectors:
  - gmail: mailbox
  - googlecalendar: events
  - googledrive: changes, file, file.update, file.trash, file.untras

